    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Passage ranking</strong> is Google's ability to identify and rank specific sections within a longer page independently of the overall page topic. Announced in October 2020 and rolled out globally in February 2021, it affected approximately <strong>7% of all search queries</strong> and fundamentally changed the ROI calculation for long-form content.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Launched</div>
            <div class="tms-value">February 2021</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Query impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~7% of searches</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Before passage ranking, Google evaluated pages as a whole. A 4,000-word guide covering 10 subtopics might not rank for any of them if the page lacked singular focus. Passage ranking changed the calculus — now each well-structured section competes on its own merits.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is passage ranking?</h2>
        <p>Passage ranking is Google's internal name for the system that evaluates long pages at the section level. When Google processes a page, it now assigns relevance scores to individual passages — not just to the page as a whole. When a user searches, Google can match a query against those passage-level scores and surface a page whose relevant section scores higher than any dedicated page for that query.</p>
        <p>The practical implication: a comprehensive guide covering 10 subtopics can now rank for queries targeting any one of those 10 subtopics, even if no single subtopic is the primary focus of the page.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's own distinction</div>
          <p>Google has clarified that "passage indexing" is a misnomer — pages are still indexed as whole documents. What changed is the <strong>ranking</strong> step: Google's ranking algorithm can now evaluate individual passages and use those scores alongside page-level scores when matching queries.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why passage ranking matters for SEO</h2>
        <p>Three concrete ways passage ranking changes what works:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Single guides replace content farms.</strong> A well-structured 5,000-word pillar page can rank for dozens of passage-level queries. Publishing 30 deep articles per month creates hundreds of passage-level opportunities — far more effective than publishing 100 thin pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Long-tail queries become easier to capture.</strong> Specific, low-competition queries (the ones that convert best) often find their exact answer buried in a comprehensive guide. Passage ranking surfaces those answers without requiring a dedicated page for each query.</li>
          <li><strong>Heading structure becomes a ranking signal.</strong> Clear, descriptive H2 and H3 headings help Google identify passage boundaries and assign relevance scores. Every vague heading ("More information") is a missed ranking opportunity.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How passage ranking works</h2>
        <p>Google uses natural language understanding — specifically BERT-based models — to process the following at index time:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Page segmentation.</strong> Google divides the page into topical passages using heading tags, paragraph breaks, and semantic topic shifts as boundaries.</li>
          <li><strong>Passage-level scoring.</strong> Each passage receives an independent relevance score for the query types it could match.</li>
          <li><strong>Query matching at ranking time.</strong> When a user searches, Google compares the query against both page-level and passage-level scores. If a passage within a page scores higher than any dedicated page, that page ranks — surfacing the user on the full page near the relevant section.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># How Google processes a long-form guide</span><br>
          Page: "Complete Vegetable Gardening Guide" (4,500 words)<br>
          <br>
