                <td>Low</td>
                <td>Page already has singular focus; whole-page ranking is more effective</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real passage ranking examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Legal guide capturing 18 query variations</h3>
        <p>A law firm published a 4,000-word LLC formation guide. Section 7 covered "LLC tax treatment vs. S-corp" in 220 focused words with a descriptive H2. After February 2021, that single section began ranking for 18 different query variations related to LLC taxation — all from one URL that was primarily about LLC formation, not taxation.</p>

        <h3>2. HVAC guide generating filter-change leads</h3>
        <p>An HVAC company's AC maintenance guide had a focused section answering "how often to change AC filters" — one direct answer in the first sentence, followed by a table of filter types and recommended frequencies. Passage ranking surfaced that section for filter-change queries, generating service leads from users who never read the full guide.</p>

        <h3>3. B2B SaaS capturing 43 PAA queries</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS company publishing 30 in-depth articles monthly found passage-level queries appearing in People Also Ask boxes for 43 different queries from a single 3,200-word article. PAA clicks accounted for 18% of that article's organic visits — all from passage-level relevance, not page-level rankings.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Passage ranking vs. topic clusters — which to prioritize?</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Prioritize passage ranking (comprehensive guides)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>One authoritative URL per topic is the goal</li>
              <li>Domain authority is moderate — consolidate signals</li>
              <li>You want multiple queries from one content investment</li>
              <li>Audience reads in depth before converting</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Prioritize topic clusters (dedicated pages)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Each subtopic has significant standalone search volume</li>
              <li>You need separate conversion paths per topic</li>
              <li>Domain authority supports many indexed URLs</li>
              <li>Different buyer personas need distinct entry points</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for passage ranking optimization</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Write descriptive H2s that match queries.</strong> "How to Prevent Aphids on Tomato Plants" outperforms "Pest Control Tips" because it matches the specific query the passage should rank for.</li>
          <li><strong>Open each section with a direct answer.</strong> Google extracts the opening of a passage most reliably. Answer the section's core question in the first sentence, then elaborate.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep paragraphs focused on one idea.</strong> Multi-idea paragraphs blur passage boundaries and dilute relevance scores for any single query.</li>
          <li><strong>Add FAQ sections to every long article.</strong> FAQ-format content creates naturally bounded passages — one question, one concise answer — optimized for both passage ranking and featured snippet extraction.</li>
          <li><strong>Target 1,500+ words with 8+ distinct H2 sections.</strong> The more passages a page contains, the more query variations it can rank for. Aim for at least one section per major user question in the topic area.</li>
          <li><strong>Update older long-form content first.</strong> Adding clear H2 structure and focused paragraphs to existing guides is the fastest way to capture passage-level ranking opportunities already within reach.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — vague heading tags</div>
          <p>Headings like "More Details," "Overview," and "Tips" give Google no passage-level signal. Every H2 and H3 should be specific enough that a user could judge from the heading alone whether that section answers their question. If the heading doesn't reflect a real query, neither does the passage.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common passage ranking mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Conflating passage ranking with featured snippets</strong> — they are complementary but distinct. Passage ranking affects which page appears; featured snippets affect how the answer is displayed.</li>
          <li><strong>Publishing thin pages instead of comprehensive guides</strong> — passage ranking rewards depth. Ten thin pages lose to one comprehensive guide with ten well-structured sections.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring word count thresholds</strong> — pages under 800 words rarely have enough distinct sections to benefit from passage-level evaluation.</li>
          <li><strong>Using keyword-stuffed headings</strong> — BERT understands intent, not just keywords. Unnatural headings built around keyword density confuse passage boundaries without improving relevance scores.</li>
          <li><strong>Neglecting internal linking to specific sections</strong> — linking to anchor IDs within pages helps Google understand which passages are most authoritative within a guide.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
